The '''A1068''' is a road in northern [[England]] that runs from [[Seaton Burn]] in [[North Tyneside]] to [[Alnwick]] in [[Northumberland]].<ref name=OS81>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 81 ''Alnwick & Morpeth (Rothbury & Amble)''|ISBN= 9780319242094 |publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2014}}</ref> The section between [[Ellington, Northumberland|Ellington]] and [[Alnmouth]] is signposted as part of the ''Northumberland Coastal Route''.<ref>{{cite web|title=SABRE: A1068|url=http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A1068|website=www.sabre-roads.org.uk|publisher=The Society for All British and Irish Road Enthusiasts|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>


==Route==
The A1068 begins at a [[roundabout]] with the [[A19 road]] at Seaton Burn. It has a brief [[dual carriageway]] section before crossing from the county of Tyne and Wear into Northumberland. It is dual carriageway standard again past [[Nelson Village]], and [[concurrency (road)|joins the route of]] the [[A192 road]] for about {{convert|1|mi}}. It continues through the town of [[Bedlington]] where it meets the [[A193 road]] and beyond the town it has a junction with the [[A196 road]] (to [[Morpeth, Northumberland|Morpeth]]). It joins the route of the [[A197 road (England)|A197 road]] for about {{convert|1|mi}} close to the town of [[Ashington]]. It re-emerges and heads in a north-easterly direction until it reaches the roundabout with the [[A189 road]]. From its junction with the A189 the A1068 gains [[primary status]] and heads roughly north. It passes the coastal town of [[Amble]] and the villages of [[Warkworth, Northumberland|Warkworth]] and [[Alnmouth]], crossing the [[River Aln]] at [[Lesbury]] before reaching the town of [[Alnwick]]. The road terminates at its junction with the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]].

