{{For|the [[Yann Tiersen]] album|Dust Lane (album)}}
[[Image:M104 ngc4594 sombrero galaxy hi-res.jpg|thumb|alt=The dark band of the "dust lane" is clearly visible against the brighter background of stars within the Sombrero Galaxy.|The [[Sombrero Galaxy]] features a prominent dust lane.]]
A '''dust lane''' is a relatively dense obscuring band of [[interstellar dust]], observed as a dark swath against the background of a brighter object, especially a [[galaxy]]. These dust lanes can usually be seen in [[spiral galaxies]] (e.g., the [[Milky Way]]) when viewed from the edge. Due to the dense and relatively thick nature of this dust, light from the galaxy is [[Extinction (astronomy)|reduced by several magnitudes]]. In the Milky Way, this reduction of light makes it impossible to see the light from the central [[Bulge (astronomy)|bulge of the galaxy]] from Earth. This dust, as well as the gasses also found within these lanes, mix together and combine to [[Star formation|form]] stars and [[Planet|planets]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Galaxies in the Universe|last=Sparke|first=L. S.|last2=Gallagher, III|first2=J. S.|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2007|isbn=978-0-521-67186-6|location=University Printing House, Cambridge CB2 *BS, United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref>
